I want to display a set of 10 small widgets across a web page line, using HTML's css grid syntax. Let's say my widgets are like this:
```
<x-spinner crsr="101" wt="1" bclr="rgba(0,55,255,.25)"></x-spinner>
```
except that the `wt` attribute increments from 1 to 10.
What would the grid layout look like?
> To display a set of 10 widgets across a web page line using CSS Grid, you would
> first need to create a container for your widgets and apply the grid layout to
> that container. Here's an example:
> 
> ```html
> <div class="grid-container">
>     <x-spinner crsr="101" wt="1" bclr="rgba(0,55,255,.25)"></x-spinner>
>     <x-spinner crsr="101" wt="2" bclr="rgba(0,55,255,.25)"></x-spinner>
>     <!-- ... -->
>     <x-spinner crsr="101" wt="10" bclr="rgba(0,55,255,.25)"></x-spinner>
> </div>
> ```
> 
> Then, in your CSS, you would define the grid layout for the container:
> 
> ```css
> .grid-container {
>     display: grid;
>     grid-template-columns: repeat(10, 1fr);
>     gap: 10px; /* optional: adds some space between the widgets */
> }
> ```
> 
> In this example, `grid-template-columns: repeat(10, 1fr);` creates a grid with
> 10 columns of equal width. The `1fr` unit represents a fraction of the available
> space in the grid container.
> 
> The `gap` property is optional and adds some space between the widgets. You can
> adjust the value or remove this property according to your needs.
> 
> Please note that the actual appearance of the widgets will also depend on their
> own styles and the styles of their parent elements.

What should I change to make that wrap if the screen is narrow?
> To make the grid items wrap when the screen is narrow, you can use CSS Grid's
> auto-fill or auto-fit along with minmax. Here's how you can do it:
> 
> ```css
> .grid-container {
>     display: grid;
>     grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(100px, 1fr));
>     gap: 10px;
> }
> ```
> 
> In this example, `repeat(auto-fill, minmax(100px, 1fr))` creates as many columns
> as can fit without the columns dropping below 100px in width. When the columns
> can't fit within the container, they will wrap to the next line.
> 
> The `minmax(100px, 1fr)` function sets a minimum width of 100px and a maximum
> width of 1fr for the columns. You can adjust the minimum width according to your
> needs.
> 
> Please note that this will only work if the container has a defined width or if
> it's within a container that has a defined width. If the container's width is
> not defined, the grid items won't know when to start wrapping.

How can I calculate the difference between font-size and line-height in Javascript?
> To calculate the difference between `font-size` and `line-height` in JavaScript,
> you first need to get these values from the element. You can use the
> `window.getComputedStyle()` method to get the computed style of an element.
> 
> Here's an example:
> 
> ```javascript
> // Get the element
> var element = document.getElementById('myElement');
> 
> // Get the computed style of the element
> var style = window.getComputedStyle(element);
> 
> // Get the font-size and line-height
> var fontSize = parseFloat(style.getPropertyValue('font-size'));
> var lineHeight = parseFloat(style.getPropertyValue('line-height'));
> 
> // Calculate the difference
> var difference = lineHeight - fontSize;
> 
> console.log(difference);
> ```
> 
> In this example, `getElementById('myElement')` gets the element with the ID of
> 'myElement'. `getComputedStyle(element)` gets the computed style of the element.
> `getPropertyValue('font-size')` and `getPropertyValue('line-height')` get the
> `font-size` and `line-height` of the element, respectively.
> 
> The `parseFloat()` function is used to convert the `font-size` and `line-height`
> from strings to numbers (they are returned as strings with units from
> `getPropertyValue()`).
> 
> Finally, `lineHeight - fontSize` calculates the difference between the
> `line-height` and `font-size`.
> 
> Please note that this will only work if the `line-height` is set in the same
> units as the `font-size`. If the `line-height` is set as a unitless number
> (which is a multiplier of the `font-size`), you'll need to multiply the
> `font-size` by the `line-height` to get the actual `line-height` in pixels.

